n_e = n_h = n_i

n_i(\text{Si at 300 K}) \approx 1.5 \times 10^{16} \text{ m}^{-3}
n_i(\text{Ge at 300 K}) \approx 2.4 \times 10^{19} \text{ m}^{-3}

n_e \approx N_D, \quad n_h = \frac{n_i^2}{N_D}

N_D = donor concentration

Electrons are majority carriers, holes are minority carriers.

n_h \approx N_A, \quad n_e = \frac{n_i^2}{N_A}

N_A = acceptor concentration

Holes are majority carriers, electrons are minority carriers.

V_0 \approx 0.7 \text{ V (Si)}
V_0 \approx 0.3 \text{ V (Ge)}

Forward bias: effective barrier = V_0 - V
Reverse bias: effective barrier = V_0 + V

r_d = \frac{\Delta V}{\Delta I}

Forward bias: r_d is small (few \Omega)
Reverse bias: r_d is very large (M\Omega)

V_{\text{dc}} = \frac{V_0}{\pi}

I_{\text{dc}} = \frac{I_0}{\pi}

Output frequency = f_{\text{input}}

(If input is 50 Hz, output is 50 Hz)

V_{\text{dc}} = \frac{2V_0}{\pi}

I_{\text{dc}} = \frac{2I_0}{\pi}

Output frequency = 2f_{\text{input}}

(If input is 50 Hz, output is 100 Hz)

\beta = \frac{\alpha}{1 - \alpha}

\alpha = \frac{\beta}{1 + \beta}

Example: If \alpha = 0.98, then \beta = 0.98/0.02 = 49

A_V = -\beta \frac{R_C}{R_{\text{in}}}

Negative sign: 180^\circ phase shift between input and output.

Power gain = \beta^2 \times \frac{R_C}{R_{\text{in}}}

V_{\text{out}} = V_Z = \text{constant}

I_S = \frac{V_{\text{in}} - V_Z}{R_S}

I_Z = I_S - I_L

R_S = series resistance, I_L = load current

E = h\nu = \frac{hc}{\lambda}

The colour of LED depends on the band gap of the semiconductor.

GaAs: infrared, GaAsP: red/yellow, GaP: green, GaN: blue
